3bc357.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc357.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3bc377"><a class="hover" title="Returnees collect water at a well in Kabul.<br>© UNHCR/N.Behring" rel="lightbox[49c3bc205]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc377.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3bc377.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc377.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3bc397"><a class="hover" title="Returning with her family from Pakistan, 11-year-old Aliyah Sarwaree (L) has started attending school in Kabul.<br>© UNHCR/N.Behring" rel="lightbox[49c3bc205]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc397.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3bc397.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc397.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3bc3b7"><a class="hover" title="Fazila, 32, a returnee from Peshawar, has gone right back to work in her beauty parlour in Kabul.<br>© UNHCR/N.Behring" rel="lightbox[49c3bc205]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc3b7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3bc3b7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3bc3b7.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Afghanistan: Rebuilding a War-Torn Country</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-49c3c8530"><h2>Home Without Land</h2><p>Land is hot property in mountainous Afghanistan, and the lack of it is a major reason Afghans in exile do not want to return.</p>

<p>Although landless returnees are eligible for the Afghan government's land allocation scheme, demand far outstrips supply. By the end of 2007, the authorities were developing 14 settlements countrywide. Nearly 300,000 returnee families had applied for land, out of which 61,000 had been selected and 3,400 families had actually moved into the settlements.</p>

<p>Desperate returnees sometimes have to camp in open areas or squat in abandoned buildings. Others occupy disputed land where aid agencies are not allowed to build permanent structures such as wells or schools.</p>

<p>One resilient community planted itself in a desert area called Tangi in eastern Afghanistan. With help from the Afghan private sector and the international community, water, homes, mosques and other facilities have sprouted &#8211; proof that the right investment and commitment can turn barren land into the good earth.</p>

<p>Posted on 31 January 2008</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-49c3c8530" title="Home Without Land"><li class="none" id="li-49c3c85311"><a class="hover" title="Afghan returnees are rebuilding their lives in areas that saw some of the worst fighting during more than two decades of strife. The village of Tangi, some five miles from the border with Pakistan was a strategic mujahideen checkpoint. Today, 250 returnee families are living there with UNHCR assistance.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c85311.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c85311.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c85311', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c85311', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c85311.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c8590"><a class="hover" title="More than half of the Afghan refugees coming to Afghanistan to rebuild their lives were born in exile and raised in a different cultural environment. These children, coming back from Pakistan and Iran, find the challenges of integration particularly difficult.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8590.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8590.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8590', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8590', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8590.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c85e7"><a class="hover" title="A young returnee collects water from one of 20 water points financed by UNHCR in the village of Tangi, close to the city of Jalalabad in eastern Afghanistan.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c85e7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c85e7.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c85e7', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c85e7', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c85e7.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c8643"><a class="hover" title="Access to water remains one of the biggest challenges for returnees to Afghanistan. Here children gather water from an outlet set up with UNHCR funding in the eastern village of Tangi.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8643.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8643.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8643', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8643', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8643.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c86a2"><a class="hover" title="Many Afghan returnees were born in exile and more than half of those coming to rebuild their lives in Afghanistan are aged under 18 years. These children are part of a community that left Pakistan in 2007 for the eastern province of Nangarhar. Their parents have no land and they are living in temporary accommodation. UNHCR is trying to secure land for them.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c86a2.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c86a2.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c86a2.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c8700"><a class="hover" title="Young Afghan returnees, born in exile in Pakistan, greet visitors to the government-funded township of Sheikh Mesri on the outskirts of Jalalabad. These children are part of a community that left Pakistan in 2007 for the eastern province of Nangarhar. Their parents have no land and they are living in temporary accommodation. UNHCR is trying to secure land for them.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8700.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8700.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8700.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c8760"><a class="hover" title="A young Afghan returnee, born in exile in Pakistan, smiles for the camera in the government-funded township of Sheikh Mesri on the outskirts of Jalalabad. The girl is part of a community that left Pakistan in 2007 for the eastern province of Nangarhar. These returnees have no land and they are living in temporary accommodation. UNHCR is trying to secure land for them.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8760.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8760.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8760.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c87b3"><a class="hover" title="An Afghan returnee works on the roof of a new home in Nangarhar province.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c87b3.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c87b3.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c87b3.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c8810"><a class="hover" title="Sultan Jan left Afghanistan 15 years ago after a stray bullet killed his four-year-old daughter. Today, he lives in this tent in Sheikh Mesri along with three other families. Like many other returnees, he hopes that the government will give him a plot of land on which he can build a permanent home.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8810.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8810.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8810.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c8870"><a class="hover" title="Members of a community shura, or council, gather in Jalalabad to discuss recent developments with UNHCR representatives.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8870.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8870.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8870.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c88c9"><a class="hover" title="The community shura is landless and returned from Pakistan in 2007. Families are squatting on public land, which they hope the government will give them.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c88c9.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c88c9.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c88c9.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c8920"><a class="hover" title="UNHCR vehicles in Sheikh Mesri, near Jalalabad. The refugee agency supports the refugee settlement at Sheikh Mesri.<br>©  UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8530]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8920.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8920.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8920.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Home Without Land</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-49c3cbf8a85"><h2>Afghan Street Children Turn from Beggars to Beauticians 
</h2><p>A UNHCR-funded project in Kabul, Afghanistan, is helping to keep returnee children off the streets by teaching them to read and write, give them room to play and offer vocational training in useful skills such as tailoring, flower making, and hairstyling.</p>

<p>Every day, Afghan children ply the streets of Kabul selling anything from newspapers to chewing gum, phone cards and plastic bags. Some station themselves at busy junctions and weave through traffic waving a can of smoking coal to ward off the evil eye. Others simply beg from passing strangers.</p>

<p>There are an estimated 50,000 to 60,000 street children in the Afghan capital alone. Among them are those who could not afford an education as refugees in Iran or Pakistan, and are unable to go to school as returnees in Afghanistan because they have to work from dawn to dusk to support their families. For the past seven years, a UNHCR-funded project has been working to bring change.</p>

<p>Posted on 12 November 2008</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-49c3cbf8a85" title="Afghan Street Children Turn from Beggars to Beauticians 
"><li class="none" id="li-49c3cbf90"><a class="hover" title="Social Volunteer Foundation (SVF) is a Kabul-based NGO that was started in 2001 to help street children under 18, many of whom are returnees.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbf90.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cbf90.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cbf90', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cbf90', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbf90.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3cbfe0"><a class="hover" title="The youngsters live at home, but are often so poor they're forced to sell items in the streets or wash cars to help support their family.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbfe0.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cbfe0.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cbfe0', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cbfe0', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbfe0.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3cc034"><a class="hover" title="The beauty parlour class is the most popular, because make up is needed for every occasion - engagements, weddings and other celebrations.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc034.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc034.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cc034', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cc034', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc034.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3cc087"><a class="hover" title="Aqila (centre) is one of the returnees attending beauty class. The 13-year-old has seven sisters and three brothers. Her family returned from Karachi, Pakistan in 2006. 'We fled to Karachi when I was very young,' she says. 'My whole family did carpet weaving there; the living was hard for everyone. We were too poor to go to school.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc087.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc087.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cc087', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3cc087', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc087.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc0d7"><a class="hover" title="'When things improved in Afghanistan, we decided to come back,' Aqila says. 'Here it is fine but the security is not okay. My family is still weaving carpets but the income is unpredictable.... After I graduate, I want to set up my own beauty parlour.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc0d7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc0d7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc0d7.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc120"><a class="hover" title="Children are also taught about the Children's Rights Convention, sexual and gender based violence, and early marriage.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc120.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc120.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc120.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc175"><a class="hover" title="Khatera, 14, learns how to sew. Her family returned from Attock in Pakistan's Punjab province in 2007. Her father now works as a day labourer. 'Until recently, I only knew how to weave. I was illiterate,' Khatera says. 'Thanks to the classes here, I can now write my name in Dari.... I hope to be a good tailor and open my own shop selling women's pants and skirts.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc175.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc175.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc175.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc1c0"><a class="hover" title="A young Afghan girl in the sewing class at SVF. Under an arrangement with the Ministry of Education, children attending SVF spend half the time attending Grade 2 classes in the Afghan curriculum.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold " rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc1c0.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc1c0.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc1c0.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc210"><a class="hover" title="In addition to vocational training and school, SVF offers gymnastics and other recreational activities.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc210.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc210.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc210.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc257"><a class="hover" title="Drawing class at SVP.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc257.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc257.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc257.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc2a7"><a class="hover" title="Raza, a 15-year-old returnee from Iran, takes part in one of the drawing classes at SVP. 'I was born in Tehran. My family was there for 20 years as refugees.... We decided to come back eight months ago [in February 2008] because we faced many problems in Iran - I couldn't go to school and my father lost his job.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc2a7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc2a7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc2a7.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc2f7"><a class="hover" title="'My friend told me about the centre and free classes here,' Raza says. 'I've always liked drawing but had no chance to try. When I graduate, I want to be an artist specializing in nature.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cbf8a85]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc2f7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc2f7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc2f7.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Afghan Street Children Turn from Beggars to Beauticians 
</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-49c3c8137"><h2>The Reality of Return in Afghanistan</h2><p>Beyond the smiles of homecoming lie the harsh realities of return. With more than 5 million Afghans returning home since 2002, Afghanistan's absorption capacity is reaching saturation point.</p>

<p>Landmine awareness training at UNHCR's encashment centres &#8211; their first stop after returning from decades in exile &#8211; is a sombre reminder of the immense challenges facing this war-torn country. Many returnees and internally displaced Afghans are struggling to rebuild their lives. Some are squatting in tents in the capital, Kabul. Basic needs like shelter, land and safe drinking water are seldom met. Jobs are scarce, and long queues of men looking for work are a common sight in marketplaces.</p>

<p>Despite the obstacles, their spirit is strong. Returning Afghans &#8211; young and old, women and men &#8211; seem determined to do their bit for nation building, one brick at a time.</p>

<p>Posted on 31 January 2008</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-49c3c8137" title="The Reality of Return in Afghanistan"><li class="none" id="li-49c3c8140"><a class="hover" title="Villagers in Darkhat, Baghlan province, enjoy a break before they resume building their homes in late 2007. They are part of a group of 24 families who have been internally displaced within Afghanistan for four years. The families have bought their own plots of land to be able to rebuild their community.<br>© UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8137]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8140.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8140.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8140', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8140', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8140.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c8177"><a class="hover" title="Children from a Turkmen carpet-weaving community play in the setting sun at a refugee settlement just outside the northern city of Mazar-i-Sharif. They were born and raised in the Jalozai refugee camp in Pakistan and returned to Afghanistan with their parents in late 2007.<br>© UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox[49c3c8137]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8177.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c8177.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8177', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c8177', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c8177.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c81b7"><a class="hover" title="Returnees from the Jalozai refugee camp in Pakistan attend a lesson at the UNHCR transit centre in Jalalabad about the danger of mines. Most will continue their journey to Nangarhar province, where they will try and rebuild their lives after years in exile.<br>© UNHCR/M.Maguire" rel="lightbox