e border from Pakistan to Torkham, Afghanistan.<br>© UNHCR/R. Arnold, September 2008" rel="lightbox[49c3cb657]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cba87.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cba87.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cba87.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cbac7"><a class="hover" title="Irrigation increases the amount of land available for cultivation, allowing more returnees to earn a living.<br>© UNHCR/R. Arnold, September 2008" rel="lightbox[49c3cb657]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbac7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cbac7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbac7.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cbb07"><a class="hover" title="A needs assessment conducted in 2007 showed that the majority of Afghan returnees in the east do not make enough to provide for their families' basic needs.<br>© UNHCR/R. Arnold, September 2008" rel="lightbox[49c3cb657]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbb07.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cbb07.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbb07.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cbb47"><a class="hover" title="The generator from a UNHCR-WFP hydro project provides electricity to a mill that grinds flour - a labour-intensive activity that has traditionally been done by hand. This benefits vulnerable returnees such as female-headed households and the elderly.<br>© UNHCR/R. Arnold, September 2008" rel="lightbox[49c3cb657]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbb47.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cbb47.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cbb47.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Afghanistan: The Reality of Return</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-49c3cc347"><h2>Afghans Return Home
</h2><p><em>In the six months since some 150 families returned from Pakistan's Jalozai refugee village, they have faced land problems and ethnic tensions. Today, however, they face the prospect of spending a bitter winter in northern Afghanistan with little more for shelter than canvas tents.</em></p>
<p>After 23 years of exile in Pakistan, Qayum and his family returned home to northern Afghanistan earlier this year ago after negotiating to buy land in Sholgara district. But a local tribe refused to let Qayum and his neighbours unload their trucks. The provincial authorities moved them to their current site at Mohajir Qeshlaq. The government has promised Qayum and his neighbours land, but until individual plots can be demarcated and distributed, nobody can build. This means that the entire returnee village - some 150 families - lives under canvas. As the weather turns cold, the prospect of spending an Afghan winter in a tent becomes reality. Returnees also face a food shortage, insufficient water and lack of livelihood opportunities.</p>
<p>In an effort to help, UNHCR will provide supplies to Qayum and his community through the winter. Once the land issue is resolved, the agency will also dig wells and provide shelter assistance to the most vulnerable families at Mohajir Qeshlaq. But it will take more to turn this makeshift settlement into something they can call home.</p>

