9c3cc4e7.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc537"><a class="hover" title="Qayum's wife, Shah Bibi, and their daughter, Mastura, in front of their tent. 'People tell us it's going to be a harsh winter,' says Qayum. 'We haven't experienced winter in 23 years; it was much warmer in Pakistan. The clothes we have are not enough. And we have no blankets.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc537.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc537.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc537.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc587"><a class="hover" title="UNHCR will provide winterization supplies to help the approximately 150 Pashtun families who've returned to Mohajir Qeshlaq through the coming months.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold " rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc587.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc587.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc587.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc5e0"><a class="hover" title="Qayum's mother contributes to the family finances by spinning wool. 'It takes me five to six days to make one kilo of yarn and I get 40 Afghanis (80 cents) for it.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc5e0.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc5e0.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc5e0.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc627"><a class="hover" title="Women from nearby tents gather in Qayum's tent to talk to UNHCR staff 'It's good to come from a stranger's land to our own land. This is our country. We used to work for Pakistan's people. Now we're working for ourselves. We may have one to two years of hardship and starvation here. But life will get better.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc627.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc627.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc627.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc680"><a class="hover" title="A widowed relative lives beside Qayum's family. They've given her a tent and help her out with food.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc680.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc680.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc680.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc6d0"><a class="hover" title="Some returnees have started making bricks in anticipation of the government giving them the land in Mohajir Qeshlaq.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc6d0.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc6d0.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc6d0.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc727"><a class="hover" title="It's too close to winter to build shelters - there won't be enough sun to dry the bricks - but at least they can start digging trenches, bunkers and building small walls to stay warm during winter.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc727.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc727.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc727.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc777"><a class="hover" title="Every day, the government sends several water tankers to the site. Qayum's children fill jerry cans and bring the water back to the tent for washing and cooking.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc777.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc777.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc777.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc7c7"><a class="hover" title="Qayum's son, Akhtar, 15, fills jerry cans for the family. 'This morning a group of six to seven boys left for Pakistan to find work. I plan to go to Kabul; I hear they're calling for brick workers there. I'm resting for a few days. I know once I start, it will be hard work.'<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc7c7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc7c7.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc7c7.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc817"><a class="hover" title="Akhtar is lucky - he's managed to borrow a wheelbarrow and a donkey to carry the water up to his tent. Returnees here say the tankered water is not enough for drinking, cooking and construction (brick making). Sometimes the children have to walk to the Sholgara River about an hour away to fetch water.<br>© UNHCR/R.Arnold" rel="lightbox[49c3cc347]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc817.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3cc817.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3cc817.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3cc870"><a class="hover" title="Afghan men wait to board buses to Iran and 