4063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157ae6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1157ae6.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157ae6.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a1157c56"><a class="hover" title="A fleeting figure in the remains of a house outside Herat.<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157c56.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1157c56.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157c56.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a1157dd6"><a class="hover" title="Tents provide temporary shelter in Kabul for some Afghan returnees.<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157dd6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1157dd6.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157dd6.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a1157f46"><a class="hover" title="Land allocation schemes give landless returnees a place to build a home. More work needs to be done to improve infrastructure in these sites, such as roads, water, schools to really make a difference for returnees<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157f46.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1157f46.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1157f46.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a1158096"><a class="hover" title="Afghans in a remote village near the northern town of Kunduz constructed their own school upon returning. Villagers had waited years for the government to begin building before taking matters into their own hands. Today most of the children in the area - girls and boys - attend classes.<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1158096.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1158096.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1158096.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a115821d"><a class="hover" title="Displaced Afghan children from Helmand province in a tented encampment in Kabul.<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a115821d.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a115821d.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a115821d.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4a1158366"><a class="hover" title="In Kabul, people walk across the remains of a bridge damaged during the Soviet occupation of the 1980s.<br>© Zalmaï" rel="lightbox[4a1155d96]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1158366.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4a1158366.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4a1158366.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Afghanistan: An Uncertain Future</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-49c3c7190"><h2>Author Hosseini in Afghanistan</h2><p>UNHCR Goodwill Envoy Khaled Hosseini visited Afghanistan in early September and saw first-hand one of the UN refugee agency's largest and most complex operations. During a 10-day trip, the best-selling author visited UNHCR projects and met returnees in the northern provinces of Kunduz, Baghlan, Balkh, Parwan and Kabul. Hosseini, a former Afghan refugee now settled in the United States, noted that it would take time and effort for Afghanistan to provide returnees with adequate infrastructure and services. He urged the international community to remain committed to Afghanistan and to give the country time. Hosseini could not visit the south and parts of the east, where insecurity is impacting on the ability of UNHCR to assess needs and provide assistance to those who need it the most. Since 2003, UNHCR has helped more than 4 million refugees return to Afghanistan. This year, some 300,000 Afghan refugees have returned from Pakistan. More than 900,000 remain in Iran and 2 million in Pakistan.</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-49c3c7190" title="Author Hosseini in Afghanistan"><li class="none" id="li-49c3c7196"><a class="hover" title="Khaled Hosseini flies kites with children at the Samangan caves in Balkh province.<br>© UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7196.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c7196.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7196', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7196', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7196.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c71e7"><a class="hover" title="Khaled Hosseini hears from village elders in Baghlan province about the conditions his community is facing. This cluster of 24 families in Darkhat has no drinking water, medical facilities or schools.<br>©  UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c71e7.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c71e7.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c71e7', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c71e7', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c71e7.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c7230"><a class="hover" title="Many of those returning are widows with small children. This woman is one of thousands of beneficiaries of the UNHCR shelter programme in Pul-i-Khumri, northern Afghanistan.<br>©  UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7230.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c7230.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7230', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7230', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7230.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-49c3c7277"><a class="hover" title="Khaled Hosseini hears how refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan get mine awareness training, medical assistance, legal aid and a start up cash package when they arrive in UNHCR centres.<br>©  UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7277.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c7277.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7277', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-49c3c7277', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7277.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c72c3"><a class="hover" title="Khaled Hosseini spoke to Afghan President Hamid Karzai about the conditions he had witnessed in the returnee settlements during his visit.<br>©  UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c72c3.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c72c3.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c72c3.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-49c3c7300"><a class="hover" title="Khaled Hosseini tours a UNHCR shelter project with humanitarian project officer, Alex Mundt, in Kunduz. Those living here returned from Iran three years ago.<br>©  UNHCR/T.Irwin, September 2007" rel="lightbox[49c3c7190]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7300.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/49c3c7300.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/49c3c7300.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Author Hosseini in Afghanistan</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-4d8b5eb16"><h2>Angelina Jolie promotes reintegration of Afghan returnees</h2><p>UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie in March 2011 returned to Afghanistan. On her second trip to the country, the acclaimed actress called for greater focus to be put on the reintegration of former refugees. More than 5.5 million refugees have returned since 2002, mainly from Pakistan and Iran, and now make up 20 per cent of the population. UNHCR is concerned that too many of these refugees continue to live without jobs, shelter and other basic needs.</p>
<p>Jolie caught up with several families she had met in 2008, still living in a dilapidated warehouse in Kabul. She was moved to see the families struggling to survive in the cold damp building. Children spend their days washing cars for money instead of attending school; the old and sick told Jolie of their pain to be such a burden on the young.</p>
<p>The actress also visited returned refugees living on the Alice Ghan and Barikab land allocation schemes north of Kabul. The returnees told her they were grateful for their houses but needed help with livelihoods. Jolie also visited Qala Gadu village, where she is funding the construction of a girls' primary school.</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-4d8b5eb16" title="Angelina Jolie promotes reintegration of Afghan returnees"><li class="none" id="li-4d8b2f476"><a class="hover" title="When UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie last met Khanum Gul, the Afghan woman's little boy was just 14 days old. Today Samir is more than two years old, but suffers from medical problems. He and his family live in a makeshift settlement in a former bus depot in Kabul city. <br>© UNHCR/J. Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2f476.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b2f476.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2f476', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2f476', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2f476.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4d8b2f886"><a class="hover" title="Sixty-five-year-old Khalil Rahman at his makeshift home on the former Tamil Mill bus depot in Kabul. Khalil and his family returned to Afghanistan in 2002 from Pakistan, where he worked in a brick factory. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2f886.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b2f886.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2f886', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2f886', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2f886.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4d8b2fba6"><a class="hover" title="UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie meets with 70-year-old Bibi Zam Jan at her makeshift home on the Tamil Mill site in Kabul. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2fba6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b2fba6.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2fba6', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2fba6', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2fba6.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4d8b2fea6"><a class="hover" title="UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie and staff at the Barikab land allocation scheme listen to the concerns of impoverished Afghans returning from years of exile overseas.<br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2fea6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b2fea6.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2fea6', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4d8b2fea6', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b2fea6.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4d8b30166"><a class="hover" title="UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie presents educational materials to students at a school she is funding in Qala Gudar village, north of Kabul. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b30166.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b30166.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b30166.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4d8b30426"><a class="hover" title="Schoolgirls wait to meet UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador Angelina Jolie in the village of Qala Gudar, which is located some 30 kilometres north of Kabul. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4d8b5eb16]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b30426.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4d8b30426.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4d8b30426.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>Angelina Jolie promotes reintegration of Afghan returnees</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-4dee32c06"><h2>More focus needed on reintegration of former Afghan refugees</h2><p>Many of the more than 5.5 million Afghan refugees who have returned home since 2002 are still struggling to survive. Lack of land, job opportunities and other services, combined with poor security in some places, has caused many returnees to head to urban areas. While cities offer the promise of informal day labour, the rising cost of rental accommodation and basic commodities relegate many returnees to life in one of the informal settlements which have mushroomed across Kabul in recent years. Some families are living under canvases and the constant threat of eviction, while others have gained a toe-hold in abandoned buildings around the city.</p>
<p>UNHCR gives humanitarian assistance to the most vulnerable, and is currently rallying support from donors and humanitarian and development agencies to redouble efforts to help returning refugees reintegrate in Afghanistan.</p>

</div><ul class="gallery" id="inlineGallery-4dee32c06" title="More focus needed on reintegration of former Afghan refugees"><li class="none" id="li-4dee1be73"><a class="hover" title="Twelve-year-old Farishta peers outside the dilapidated warehouse where she and her returnee family have lived for eight years.  Farishta is the only child out of eight siblings who attends school. Education is accessible but many families send their children to work to help support the family. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1be73.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1be73.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1be73', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1be73', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1be73.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4dee1c1d6"><a class="hover" title="Farishta's mother, Zazabour,  pictured with  her husband, Ghuman, and youngest son, Sameed. The 10 members of the family live in a makeshift shelter in a dilapidated warehouse building. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c1d6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1c1d6.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c1d6', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c1d6', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c1d6.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4dee1c4b6"><a class="hover" title="Times are tough for Farishta's family. To make ends meet, the children spend their days looking for recyclable items in the nearby dump and sometimes Zazabour must go out and  beg. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c4b6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1c4b6.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c4b6', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c4b6', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c4b6.jpg"></a></li><li class="none" id="li-4dee1c776"><a class="hover" title="Ghuman earns between 80-90 Afghanis (approx. US$2) per day from using his 'karachi' or wheelbarrow to transport goods around the market areas. Though he works all day this is still not enough to support his family. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c776.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1c776.jpg" onmouseover="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c776', true)" onmouseout="MenuHoverEffect('li-4dee1c776', false)"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1c776.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1cb76"><a class="hover" title="Hundreds of day labourers seek work daily in the centre of Kabul. Low literacy rates and job skills limit access to employment other than low-paying daily wage labour or pushing wheelbarrows in the market.<br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1cb76.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1cb76.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1cb76.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1ce06"><a class="hover" title="Khalil, 65, stands in his makeshift home in Kabul city where he and his family live. He returned to Afghanistan in 2002 to find his home in Parwan destroyed by fighting. He and his wife and six children all live in one room in a dilapidated warehouse building. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1ce06.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1ce06.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1ce06.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1d09120"><a class="hover" title="Khalil says he is not fit enough to do physical labour and so must rely on his sons selling plastic bags in the market, along with charity from neighbours and distributions from the UN refugee agency and the World Food Programme. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d09120.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1d09120.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d09120.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1d556"><a class="hover" title="Khalil's physically-disabled son, Azis, lies on the floor of the family's one-room home.  The 22-year-old has never been diagnosed because the family can't afford the medical consultation or subsequent treatment.  <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d556.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1d556.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d556.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1d7e6"><a class="hover" title="Bibi Marjan, a mother of six, returned from Iran in 2002, having fled fighting in Kabul nearly 10 years before. With her husband chronically ill, she sends her two youngest sons out to work washing cars. Sometimes she must supplement this income by begging.<br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d7e6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1d7e6.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1d7e6.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1dab6"><a class="hover" title="Bibi's sons Roman, 11, and Negmar, 10, walk into the city daily to wash cars for 40 Afghanis (US$1) each. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1dab6.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1dab6.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1dab6.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1dd46"><a class="hover" title="The boys wash an average of two cars every day. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1dd46.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1dd46.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1dd46.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1e086"><a class="hover" title="Bibi's oldest child, 15-year-old Marja, no longer goes to school as her mother fears she will be kidnapped for marriage. Bibi says the girl has received many offers of money and marriage proposals in recent months. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e086.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1e086.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e086.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1e416"><a class="hover" title="A widowed mother of three, Mariam supports her family by cooking 'bolony', a fried bread filled with chopped spinach and onion, in the courtyard of their home in an abandoned building. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e416.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1e416.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e416.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1e696"><a class="hover" title="Every morning Mariam makes between 20-30 pieces of fried bread, which her oldest son Kadir sells in the city centre. Each piece of bread sells for 5 Afghanis. (US$ 0.10)<br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e696.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1e696.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e696.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1e936"><a class="hover" title="Kadir leaves the Tamil Mill Bus site and heads for the market to sell bread.  Kadir says some days he can sell everything by 2pm, other days it takes all day. Any unsold bread is eaten by the family. <br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e936.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1e936.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1e936.jpg"></a></li><li class="hidden" id="li-4dee1ec16"><a class="hover" title="Kadir serves a customer.
<br>© UNHCR/J.Tanner" rel="lightbox[4dee32c06]" style="background-image: url('/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1ec16.jpg');" href="/web/20120604063834/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb1/4dee1ec16.jpg"><img class="hide" alt="" src="/web/20120604063834im_/http://www.unhcr.org/thumb0/4dee1ec16.jpg"></a></li></ul><div class="clear-both"></div><h4>More focus needed on reintegration of former Afghan refugees</h4></div><div class="rightComponent"><div class="inlineGBlurb hidTag" id="inlineGBlurb-4fc4978c2"><h2>Afghan Refugees in Iran </h2><p>At a recent conference in Geneva, the international community endorsed a "solutions strategy" for millions of Afghan refugees and those returning to Afghanistan after years in exile. The plan, drawn up between Afghanistan, Iran, Pakistan and UNHCR, aims to support repatriation, sustainable reintegration and assistance to host countries.</p>
<p>It will benefit refugee returnees to Afghanistan as well as 3 million Afghan refugees, including 1 million in Iran and 1.7 million in Pakistan.</p>
<p>Many of the refugees in Iran have been living there for more than three decades. This photo set captures the lives of some of these exiles, who wait in hope of a lasting solution to their situation.</p>

